{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1060"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1060"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.14,0.09,0.03,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53690"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1060"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39161"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48778"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53690"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a single episode of upper abdominal pain. The pain came on suddenly, lasted about 30 minutes, and then settled. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks about two glasses of wine on weekends. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. An ultrasound examination is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polycystic liver disease","Haemangioma","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Metastatic deposits","Hydatid disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound image shows a large cystic lesion occupying much of the right lobe of the liver. The lesion is homogeneous in appearance, with smooth borders and no septae. Notably, there appears to be a cyst within the cyst, which is characteristic of a daughter cyst. These features are typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E. Hydatid cysts commonly occur in the liver and lungs, and less frequently in bones, kidneys, spleen, muscle, and central nervous system. Given the size of the cyst and the patient\u0027s brief, self-limiting symptoms, this is likely an incidental finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with multiple cysts (more than 20) of varying sizes, each larger than 1 cm. These cysts usually have no septations and show strong posterior wall acoustic enhancement on ultrasound, which is not the case in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemangiomas\u003C/strong\u003E are solid lesions that appear echogenic compared to the surrounding liver parenchyma on ultrasound. They typically show minimal or absent vascularity on Doppler imaging due to sluggish internal blood flow. The cystic nature of the lesion in this image is inconsistent with a haemangioma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a solid lesion with an echotexture similar to the adjacent liver tissue. It often features a central hypoechoic scar and may show spoke-like vessels on Doppler imaging. The large cystic appearance in this image does not match these characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic deposits\u003C/strong\u003E in the liver are often mixed solid and necrotic lesions rather than purely cystic. They typically have irregular contours, peripheral vascularity, and are usually multifocal. The smooth-bordered, homogeneous cystic lesion seen here is not consistent with metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydatid disease, while now relatively uncommon in Australia due to improved animal husbandry practices and hygiene, still accounts for about 100 diagnosed cases annually. The life cycle of \u003Cem\u003EE. granulosus\u003C/em\u003E involves dogs and other canines as the primary host, with the tapeworm living in their small intestine. Eggs are shed in faeces and may be ingested by grazing animals (typically sheep), which become intermediate hosts. In these hosts, the eggs hatch in the gut, and the oncosphere migrates to solid organs, usually the liver or lungs, where it develops into a cyst. Humans become accidental intermediate hosts through close contact with infected definitive hosts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of hydatid disease in Australia are usually an incidental finding.","Hydatid cysts typically appear as large, homogeneous cystic lesions with smooth borders on ultrasound, often containing daughter cysts.","Echinococcus granulosus, the causative organism of hydatid disease, has a life cycle involving dogs as the primary host and grazing animals as intermediate hosts."],"references":["Keong B, Wilkie B, Sutherland T, et al. Hepatic cystic echinococcosis in Australia: an update on diagnosis and management. ANZ J Surg 2018;88:26\u201331. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29024292/","Liver cysts. In: Teach Me Surgery [Online]. 2023.  Available at: https://teachmesurgery.com/hpb/liver/liver-cysts/","Sutherland T. Demystifying Abdominal Ultrasound. Australin Family Physician. 2009;38(10).  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/a551027c-ed92-49ca-964d-4e23b3705381/Demystifying-abdominal-ultrasound.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1060"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19646"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19646"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/da30e5af-504e-4f31-bf9f-ef1dde0f23c9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/da30e5af-504e-4f31-bf9f-ef1dde0f23c9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":561,"height":423}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-25T10:36:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-25T10:37:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1060"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53690"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology